"...buya, Shibuya Station. This is the final stop. Please make sure you have all your belongings..."

A sharp, feminine voice pierced my eardrums.

I snapped to my senses. My cheek, pressed against the cold windowpane, felt numb. As I blinked slowly, what entered my vision wasn't a blue velvet room, but the familiar, tedious interior of the train. Beyond the window reflecting the fluorescent lights, the bright platform of Shibuya Station was gliding into view.

The remnants of the dream I'd been having until just a moment ago lingered faintly in my mind. An old man with a long nose, a blue room, an incomprehensible contract... But the once-vivid sensations had already faded, remaining only as fragmented images. Like an old film, the memory rapidly vanished amidst crackling static.

"This is Shibuya, the terminal station. Goodbye."

Ding-dong. With a cheerful chime, the train came to a complete halt. With a *psshh* sound, the doors opened, and as if on cue, people started pouring out. Other passengers who had been dozing off, and even those with their faces buried in their smartphones, all rose as if by some unspoken agreement and headed for the exit.

Swept along by the current of people, I dazedly rose from my seat. I adjusted the strap of the bag on my shoulder and dragged my heavy, still-drowsy body out onto the platform. The sudden blast of the city's noise and the energy of the crowd shattered even the final fragments of my dream.
